00:24:08.090 --> 00:24:14.000 position:72%
So another question -- and I encourage all of
you guys who are listening to also submit one,

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:19.610 position:61%
but I'll give you one more, Sahr, which
is to ask you about Wilson's influence

00:24:19.610 --> 00:24:26.060 position:70%
on American foreign policy and how or whether
it shaped American foreign policy today.

00:24:26.060 --> 00:24:30.410 position:58%
Sort of this idea of an international
perspective, international bodies,

00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:34.720
and the United States involvement
in those bodies and sort of a frame

00:24:34.720 --> 00:24:37.980
for American foreign policy
the last century or so.

00:24:37.980 --> 00:24:41.510 position:73%
Are we moving out of an era of Wilsonism today?

00:24:41.510 --> 00:24:43.740
How would you talk about that?

00:24:43.740 --> 00:24:49.030 position:64%
&gt;&gt; So you know, Wilson is not necessarily
the most popular president today

00:24:49.030 --> 00:24:57.330 position:61%
but I think he is very important both
for domestic policy and foreign policy.

00:24:57.330 --> 00:25:02.200 position:72%
In foreign policy, it's really where he made
his mark although I think it would have been a

00:25:02.200 --> 00:25:06.890
surprise to Wilson to think
that international relations is

00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:10.480
where he really would have
had the greatest influence.

00:25:10.480 --> 00:25:15.940
But in international relations,
kind of how people often think

00:25:15.940 --> 00:25:20.320
about Wilson still today is
Wilson really embodied this idea

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:23.910 position:58%
of idealism in international affairs.

00:25:23.910 --> 00:25:31.420 position:56%
And it's a question that people
come back to again and again dealing

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:35.400
with today's current events
and thinking about the history

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:39.440
of American foreign relations
and Wilson in particular.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:47.300 position:72%
I mean, this idea of Wilsonianism, a term that
has been used to mean many different things,

00:25:47.300 --> 00:25:55.970 position:70%
although generally it's used to mean the idea
of pursuing some kind of universal ideals

00:25:55.970 --> 00:26:01.060 position:67%
as opposed to narrow American
self-interest or narrow national interests.

00:26:01.060 --> 00:26:05.310
It's also been used to mean
the spread of democracy abroad,

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:12.050 position:63%
which in my talk I said I think that's
slightly a misreading of Woodrow Wilson,

00:26:12.050 --> 00:26:20.540 position:75%
even though he did pick up the chance for
self-determination during World War I and follow

00:26:20.540 --> 00:26:22.860
that through to a certain degree.

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:30.150 position:70%
Although, Wilson certainly wasn't arguing to
get rid of imperialism and colonies dominated

00:26:30.150 --> 00:26:33.790 position:69%
by the European powers throughout the world.

00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:36.740 position:69%
He had somewhat ambivalent views about that.

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:44.870
But in terms of whether we're
leaving an era of Wilsonianism,

00:26:44.870 --> 00:26:47.600 position:64%
I think it's going to be -- I mean, yeah.

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:48.840
I'm a historian.

00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:56.890 position:75%
One of the last things you want me to do is make
predictions about the future but I would say

00:26:56.890 --> 00:27:04.170
that considering questions about
the role of ideals versus interest

00:27:04.170 --> 00:27:08.610 position:66%
and international relations is going to
be a question that we're going to continue

00:27:08.610 --> 00:27:13.110 position:69%
to struggle with for the foreseeable future.

